04867nam a22008775i 9780228014959DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280149597 a10.1515/97802280149592doi  a(DE-B1597)656378  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDA813b.C66 2023 7aHIS0370602bisacsh04a941.0812231 aConnolly, Michael J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJacobitism in Britain and the United States, 1880–1910 /cMichael J. Connolly. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Transatlantic Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Jacobitism in the Age of Victoria -- tLegitimacy and Obedience: The Ideas behind Jacobite Resurgence -- t“Now the Moon Is Blighted”: The Victorian Jacobite World -- t“Authority Has a Divine Sanction”: The Early Years of the White Rose in Britain -- t“God Save Queen Mary”: The High Tide of Victorian Jacobitism -- t“Up with the Standard”: The White Rose Comes to America -- t“The Heresy of Popular Sovereignty”: Ralph Adams Cram and the Royal Standard -- t“The Persistence of Loyalty to Tradition”: The Decline and Fall of Victorian Jacobitism -- tConclusion “The Fault of the Years”: The Significance of the Victorian Jacobites -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late nineteenth century a resurgent Jacobite movement emerged in Britain and the United States, highlighting the virtues of the Stuart monarchs in contrast to liberal, democratic, and materialist Victorian Britain and Gilded Age America. Compared with similarly aligned protest movements of the era – socialism, anarchism, nihilism, populism, and progressivism – the rise of Jacobitism receives little attention.Born in the Glorious Revolution of 1688, Jacobitism had been in steep decline since the mid-eighteenth century. But between 1880 and 1910, Jacobite organizations popped up across Britain, then spread to the United States, publishing royalist magazines, organizing public demonstrations, offering Anglo-Catholic masses to fallen Stuart kings, and praying at Stuart statues and tombs. Michael Connolly explains the rise and fall of Anglo-American Jacobitism, places it in context, and reveals its significance as a response to and a driver of the political forces of the period. Understanding the Jacobite movement clarifies Victorian Anglo-American anxiety over liberalism, democracy, industrialization, and emerging modernity. In an age when worries over liberalism are again ascendant, Jacobitism in Britain and the United States, 1880–1910 traces the complex genealogy of this unease.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJacobitesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJacobitesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAnglicanism.  aBoston.  aCanada.  aCatholicism.  aGlorious Revolution.  aJohn Locke.  aKing Charles I.  aKing Charles II.  aKing James II.  aLiberalism.  aMarquis de Ruvigny.  aMassachusetts.  aNewEngland.  aOliver Cromwell.  aQueen Victoria.  aRalph Adams Cram.  aRitualism.  aScotland.  aStuart.  aThomas Hobbes.  aanti modernism.  aaristocracy.  aauthority.  aconservatism.  ademocracy.  aequality.  aindividualism.  alegitimism.  aliberty.  amodernity.  amonarchy.  aprogress.  aroyalist.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228014959?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228014959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228014959/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles